  1. Complete the following code to transform the data to make it daily (instead of hour/day). You need to change the XXXX to make it an appropriate line to run. Note: Use an average for continuous variables and the mode for factor variables. We also add all uses for the outcome.

Answer:

# Function thatreturns the mode of a vector
getmode <- function(v) {
   uniqv <- unique(v)
   uniqv[which.max(tabulate(match(v, uniqv)))]
}

bikedc_daily <- bikedc %>% select(-datetime) %>% group_by(date) %>%
  summarise(across(where(is.numeric) & !c(casual, registered, count), ~mean(.x, na.rm = TRUE), .names = "m_{.col}"),
    across(where(is.factor), ~getmode(.x), .names = "m_{.col}"),
    across(c(casual, registered, count), ~sum(.x), .names = "total_{.col}"))


rm(bikedc) # We will remove the bikedc dataframe from the session to free up some memory, if needed.
  1. Select 50% of the sample for training and 50% for testing, Estimate your prediction RMSE using an OLS model using all the covariates. What is your outcome variable? Are there any variable you should leave out in your data set and why/why not? Show your RMSE.

Answer:

library(rsample)
library(caret)

set.seed(100)

split <- initial_split(bikedc_daily, prop = 0.5, strata = total_count)

train.bikedc <- training(split) 
test.bikedc <- testing(split) 

lm1 <- lm(total_count ~ . - date - total_casual - total_registered, data = train.bikedc)

pred.count.lm <- predict(lm1, newdata = test.bikedc)

RMSE(pred.count.lm, test.bikedc$total_count)
## [1] 1518.088
  1. Do you think the previous model is a good prediction model or not? Talk about the advantages and disadvantages both in terms of bias and variance.

Answer: OLS models might not be the best in terms of prediction, especially because they tend to over-simplify reality, making them high-bias. Additionally, because we are just using all covariates, we might run additionally into a high-variance issue. To solve this, we should do some sort of model selection to try to hopefully select a subset of the covariates, but probably high bias is the main issue here.

  1. Using the same training/testing dataset, now use a Lasso regularization for the previous model.

  • Plot the regularization parameter vs the RMSE and interpret the plot using your own words.
  • What is the optimal shrinkage parameter?

Note: Only use 5 cross-validation folds and use the lambda_seq vector provided

lambda_seq <- c(0,10^seq(-3, 3, length = 200))

lasso1 <- train(total_count ~ . - date - total_casual - total_registered, 
                data = train.bikedc, method = "glmnet",

  1. Use bagging in combination with decision trees to get a final estimate of RMSE.

  • What covariates are the most important? Which ones are the least important?

Note: Only use 5 cross-validation folds and 15 bagged trees

Answer:

library(rpart)

bt <- train(total_count ~ . - date - total_casual - total_registered, data = train.bikedc, method = "treebag", 
            trControl = trainControl("cv", num = 5),
            nbagg = 15, control = rpart.control(cp = 0))


library(vip)

vip(bt)

pred.count.bt <- predict(bt, newdata = test.bikedc)

RMSE(pred.count.bt, test.bikedc$total_count)
## [1] 1312.815

Causal Inference

Now assume we want to estimate the effect of certain interventions to incentivize the use of bike shares

  1. Imagine that the intervention you had in mind was to reduce the price for causal riders and increase the price for registered riders. You are present in multiple cities in the US and you randomize this interventions at the city level.
  • What would your outcome(s) of interest be?

Answer: Total rides, and total rides by type of customer.

  • What would your estimand(s) of interest be? Explain it in terms of potential outcomes.

Answer: ATEs. Comparison between the rides that customers would have taken with the price change vs rides they would have taken without the price change.

  1. What would be a check that you would run to ensure that randomization was done correctly?

Answer: Balance table of covariates. Talk about if you should expect some significant differences given the number of covariates you are testing.

Unfortunately, we did not get the approval to run an RCT, but we know that NYC experienced a similar change to the one we want to test in 2012.

  1. What identification strategy would you use for this? Why do you think it would identify a causal estimate? What assumptions need to hold? Why could those assumptions fail? Give examples.

Answer: Diff-in-Diff. If both cities have similar trends over time, we could use this strategy, and there are no time-varying confounders.
